  1. Being hit by a chair is a common occurrence in WWE professional wrestling. The number of people hit upside the head with chairs can vary from program to program. Suppose that the number of chair-bashings per program is Normally distributed, with mean thirty-five (35) bashings and standard deviation of eight (8) bashings. What is the probability that one WWE program will contain less than nineteen (19) bashings or more than forty (40) bashings?
bashings.lowerpval <- pnorm(q=19,mean = 35, sd = 8, lower.tail = TRUE);bashings.lowerpval
## [1] 0.02275013
bashings.upperpval <- pnorm(q=40,mean = 35, sd = 8, lower.tail = FALSE);bashings.upperpval
## [1] 0.2659855
total.bashings <- bashings.lowerpval + bashings.upperpval; total.bashings
## [1] 0.2887357

When seeking to determine the probability within one WWE program (1 sample) of chair-bashing observations(x) of x < 19 or x > 40, the combined probability of either obsrvation is 0.2887357 or 0.289.

  1. A corporation has just received new machinery that must be installed and checked before it becomes operational. The following table shows a manager’s probability assessment for the number of days required before the machinery becomes operational:
Days 5 6 7 8 9 10
Prob. 0.06 0.21 0.37 0.20 0.13 0.06

Let A be the event “It will be more than 6 days before the machinery becomes operational,” and let B be the event “It will be less than 8 days before the machinery becomes available.”

  1. Find the probability of event A.
A.event <- 0.37 + 0.20 + 0.13 + 0.06; print(A.event)
## [1] 0.76

The probability of Event A, x > 6 days, is 0.76. There is a relatively high probability that the machinery will become operational after 6 days.

  1. Find the probability of event B.
B.event <- 0.06 + 0.21 + 0.37; print(B.event)
## [1] 0.64

The probability of Event B, x < 8 days, is 0.64. There is a relatively high probability that the machinery will become operational in under 8 days.

  1. Find the probability of the complement of event A.
complement.A <- 1 - A.event; print(complement.A)
## [1] 0.24

The probability that the machinery will be operational in under 6 days is 0.24.

  1. Find the probability of the intersection of events A and B.

In all the listed probabilities for scenarios where the machinery becomes operational, this concerns the probability where 6 < x < 8. This corresponds to 7 days, hence the probability is 0.37.

  1. Find the probability of the union of events A and B.
AandB.event <- A.event + B.event - 0.37; print(AandB.event)
## [1] 1.03

The probability of both events A and B happening are equal to 1.

  1. An ultramarathon race official has found that 68% of first time entrants and 87% ofrepeat racers finish the race. Of all entrants, 64% are repeat racers and the remainders are first time entrants.
  1. What is the probability that a randomly chosen entrant is a repeat racer who will eventually finish the race? Prob(repeat and finish) = 0.87 Prob(repeat and quit) = 1 - 0.87 = 0.13 Prob(first and finish) = 0.68 Prob(first and quit) = 1 - 0.68 = 0.32 Prob(repeat) = 0.64 Prob(first) = 1 - 0.64 = 0.36
Prob.repeat.and.finish <- 0.87
Prob.repeat <- 0.64
random.repeat.and.finish <- 0.87 * 0.64; print(random.repeat.and.finish)
## [1] 0.5568

P(random.repeat.and.finish) = 0.5568 or 0.557.

  1. Find the probability that a randomly chosen entrant will eventually finish the race.
Prob.first.and.finish <- 0.68
Prob.first <- 0.36
random.first.and.finish <- 0.68 * 0.36; print(random.first.and.finish)
## [1] 0.2448
random.finish <- random.repeat.and.finish + random.first.and.finish; print(random.finish)
## [1] 0.8016

The P(random.finish) = 0.8016 or 0.802.

  1. What is the probability that a randomly chosen entrant either is a repeat racer or will eventually finish (or both)?
repeat.or.finish <- Prob.repeat + random.finish - random.repeat.and.finish; print(repeat.or.finish)
## [1] 0.8848

The P(repeat.or.finish) = 0.8848 or 0.885.

  1. A school received a grant to offer two extracurricular clubs, art and chess. Of the students 35% signed up for art club and 40% for chess club. Of those signing up for art club 20% signed up for chess club. Prob(art) = 0.35 Prob(chess) = 0.40 Prob(chess given art) = 0.20
  1. What is the probability that a randomly selected student signed up for both clubs?
Prob.art <- 0.35
Prob.chess <- 0.40
Prob.chess.given.art <- 0.20
random.chess.given.art <- Prob.art * Prob.chess.given.art; print(random.chess.given.art)
## [1] 0.07

The probability that a randomly selected student who signed up for chess club also signed up for art club is 0.07.

  1. What is the probability that a randomly selected student who signed up for chess club also signed up for art club?
random.chess.and.art <- random.chess.given.art / Prob.chess; print(random.chess.and.art)
## [1] 0.175

The probability that a randomly selected student who signed up for chess club also signed up for art club is 0.175.

  1. What is the probability that a randomly chosen student signed up for at least one of these two clubs?
two.clubs <- Prob.art + Prob.chess - random.chess.given.art; print(two.clubs)
## [1] 0.68

The probability that a randomly chosen student signed up for at least one of these two clubs is 0.68.

Prob.no.vac <- 84/442; print(Prob.no.vac)
## [1] 0.1900452
(8 * 442) / 100 #35.36 kids
## [1] 35.36
Prob.absent <- 35/442; print(Prob.absent)
## [1] 0.07918552
84 * Prob.absent
## [1] 6.651584

P(no.vac) = 0.1900452 P(absent) = 0.07918552 = 0.08

Working from the assumption that having unvaccinated status is not related to absenteeism, then P(no.vac) has no bearing on the P(absent). The unvaccinated kids will have the same chance of being absent as the rest of the kids in the sample where n = 442. The number of kids the district’s physician will miss is 6.651584 or 6 (because you cannnot have portions of kids; the variable is discrete).

  1. (also problem 4.17/4.18 in Open Intro 3) Identify hypotheses, For each item, write the null and alternative hypotheses in words and then symbols for each of the following situations.
  1. New York is known as city that never sleeps“. A random sample of 25 New Yorkers were asked how much sleep they get per night. Do these data provide convincing evidence thatNew Yorkers on average sleep less than 8 hours a night?

Null: New Yorkers sleep eight hours per night on average. Alternative: New Yorkers sleep less than eight hours per night on average. \(H0: mu = 8\) \(HA: mu < 8\)

  1. Employers at a firm are worried about the effect of March Madness, a basketball championship held each spring in the US, on employee productivity. They estimate that on a regular business day employees spend on average 15 minutes of company time checking personal email, making personal phone calls, etc. They also collect data on how much company time employees spend on such non-business activities during March Madness. They want to determine if these data provide convincing evidence that employee productivity decreases during March Madness.

Null: Employees use 15 minutes of time per day engaged in non-business activities during March. Alternative: Employees use more than 15 minutes of time per day engaged in non-business activities during March. \(H0: mu = 15\) \(HA: mu > 15\)

  1. Since 2008, chain restaurants in California have been required to display calorie counts of each menu item. Prior to menus displaying calorie counts, the average calorie intake of diners at a restaurant was 1100 calories. After calorie counts started to be displayed on menus,a nutritionist collected data on the number of calories consumed at this restaurant from a random sample of diners. Do these data provide convincing evidence of a difference in the average calorie intake of a diners at this restaurant?

Null: Calorie consumption after the implementation of the calore count requirement is the same as before the requirement.
Alternative: Calore consumption after the implementation of the calore count requirement is NOT the same as before the requirement.
\(H0: mu = 1100\) \(HA: mu != 1100\)

  1. Based on the performance of those who took the GRE exam between July 1, 2004 and June 30, 2007, the average Verbal Reasoning score was calculated to be 462. In 2011 the average verbal score was slightly higher. Do these data provide convincing evidence that the average GRE Verbal Reasoning score has changed since 2004?

Null: There has been no change in the average GRE Verbal Reasoning Score since 2004. Alternative: There has been a change in the average GRE Verbal Reasoning Score since 2004. \(H0: mu = 462\) \(HA: mu != 462\)

  1. (also 4.30 in Open Intro 3) A food safety inspector is called upon to investigate a restau-rant with a few customer reports of poor sanitation practices. The food safety inspector uses a hypothesis testing framework to evaluate whether regulations are not being met. If he decides the restaurant is in gross violation, its license to serve food will be revoked.
  1. Write the hypotheses in words.

Null: The restaurant is NOT is gross violation of sanitation regulations. Alternative: The restarant is in gross violation of sanitation regulations.

  1. What is a Type 1 Error in this context?

In this context, a Type I Error would be concluding that the restuarant is in gross violation of sanitation regulations when it actually is not. This could be a function of setting the critical value/signficance level too low.

  1. What is a Type 2 Error in this context?

In this context, a Type II Error would be concluding that the restuarant is not in gross violation of sanitation regulations when it actually is. This could be the result of setting the critical value/significance level too high.

  1. Which error is more problematic for the restaurant owner? Why?

A Type I Error would be more immediately problematic for the restaurant owner because a finding of gross violation of sanitation regulations would result in an immediate (but hopefully temporary) closure of the restaurant until the offending issue(s) are remedied. The owner would lose revenues and expend monies to fix a problem that should not have been indicated.

  1. Which error is more problematic for the diners? Why?’ A Type II Error would be more immediately problematic for the diners at the restuarant because a finding that the restuarant is not in violation of sanitation regulations would likely result in more food-borne illness like food poisoning (which may be fatal to specific vulnerable populations). The restuarant should be closed to remedy the violations but is still open for business and is a public health threat.
